.RE
.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBabstract(Data) -> AbsTerm\fR
\fB                  when Data :: term(), AbsTerm :: abstract_expr().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts the Erlang data structure \fIData\fR into an abstract form of type \fIAbsTerm\fR. This function is the inverse of \fInormalise/1\fR.

.PP
\fIerl_parse:abstract(T)\fR is equivalent to \fIerl_parse:abstract(T, 0)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBabstract(Data, Options) -> AbsTerm\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      Data :: term(),\fR
\fB                      Options :: Location | [Option],\fR
\fB                      Option ::\fR
\fB                          {encoding, Encoding} |\fR
\fB                          {line, Line} |\fR
\fB                          {location, Location},\fR
\fB                      Encoding ::\fR
\fB                          latin1 | unicode | utf8 | none |\fR
\fB                          encoding_func(),\fR
\fB                      Line :: erl_anno:line(),\fR
\fB                      Location :: erl_anno:location(),\fR
\fB                      AbsTerm :: abstract_expr().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts the Erlang data structure \fIData\fR into an abstract form of type \fIAbsTerm\fR.

.PP
Each node of \fIAbsTerm\fR is assigned an annotation, see \fIerl_anno\fR. The annotation contains the location given by option \fIlocation\fR or by option \fIline\fR. Option \fIlocation\fR overrides option \fIline\fR. If neither option \fIlocation\fR nor option \fIline\fR is given, \fI0\fR is used as location.

.PP
Option \fIEncoding\fR is used for selecting which integer lists to be considered as strings. The default is to use the encoding returned by function \fIepp:default_encoding/0\fR. Value \fInone\fR means that no integer lists are considered as strings. \fIencoding_func()\fR is called with one integer of a list at a time; if it returns \fItrue\fR for every integer, the list is considered a string.


.RE
.B
\fBanno_from_term(Term) -> erl_parse_tree() | form_info()\fR
\fB                        when Term :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Assumes that \fITerm\fR is a term with the same structure as a \fIerl_parse\fR tree, but with terms, say \fIT\fR, where a \fIerl_parse\fR tree has collections of annotations.

.PP
Returns a \fIerl_parse\fR tree where each term \fIT\fR is replaced by the value returned by \fIerl_anno:from_term(T)\fR. The term \fITerm\fR is traversed in a depth-first, left-to-right fashion.


.RE
.B
\fBanno_to_term(Abstr) -> term()\fR
\fB                      when Abstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns a term where each collection of annotations \fIAnno\fR of the nodes of the \fIerl_parse\fR tree \fIAbstr\fR is replaced by the term returned by \fIerl_anno:to_term(Anno)\fR. The \fIerl_parse\fR tree is traversed in a depth-first, left-to-right fashion.


.RE
.B
\fBfold_anno(Fun, Acc0, Abstr) -> Acc1\fR
\fB                   when\fR
\fB                       Fun :: fun((Anno, AccIn) -> AccOut),\fR
\fB                       Anno :: erl_anno:anno(),\fR
\fB                       Acc0 :: term(),\fR
\fB                       Acc1 :: term(),\fR
\fB                       AccIn :: term(),\fR
\fB                       AccOut :: term(),\fR
\fB                       Abstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Updates an accumulator by applying \fIFun\fR on each collection of annotations of the \fIerl_parse\fR tree \fIAbstr\fR.

.PP
The first call to \fIFun\fR has \fIAccIn\fR as argument, the returned accumulator \fIAccOut\fR is passed to the next call, and so on. The final value of the accumulator is returned. The \fIerl_parse\fR tree is traversed in a depth-first, left-to-right fashion.


.RE
.B
\fBformat_error(any()) -> [char() | list()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Uses an ErrorDescriptor and returns a string that describes the error.

.PP
This function is usually called implicitly when an ErrorInfo structure is processed (see section Error Information).


.RE
.B
\fBmap_anno(Fun, Abstr) -> NewAbstr\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      Fun :: fun((Anno) -> NewAnno),\fR
\fB                      Anno :: erl_anno:anno(),\fR
\fB                      NewAnno :: erl_anno:anno(),\fR
\fB                      Abstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info(),\fR
\fB                      NewAbstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Modifies the \fIerl_parse\fR tree \fIAbstr\fR by applying \fIFun\fR on each collection of annotations of the nodes of the \fIerl_parse\fR tree. The \fIerl_parse\fR tree is traversed in a depth-first, left-to-right fashion.


.RE
.B
\fBmapfold_anno(Fun, Acc0, Abstr) -> {NewAbstr, Acc1}\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Fun :: fun((Anno, AccIn) -> {NewAnno, AccOut}),\fR
\fB                          Anno :: erl_anno:anno(),\fR
\fB                          NewAnno :: erl_anno:anno(),\fR
\fB                          Acc0 :: term(),\fR
\fB                          Acc1 :: term(),\fR
\fB                          AccIn :: term(),\fR
\fB                          AccOut :: term(),\fR
\fB                          Abstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info(),\fR
\fB                          NewAbstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Modifies the \fIerl_parse\fR tree \fIAbstr\fR by applying \fIFun\fR on each collection of annotations of the nodes of the \fIerl_parse\fR tree, while at the same time updating an accumulator.

.PP
The first call to \fIFun\fR has \fIAccIn\fR as second argument, the returned accumulator \fIAccOut\fR is passed to the next call, and so on. The modified \fIerl_parse\fR tree and the final value of the accumulator are returned. The \fIerl_parse\fR tree is traversed in a depth-first, left-to-right fashion.


.RE
.B
\fBnew_anno(Term) -> Abstr\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      Term :: term(),\fR
\fB                      Abstr :: erl_parse_tree() | form_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Assumes that \fITerm\fR is a term with the same structure as a \fIerl_parse\fR tree, but with locations where a \fIerl_parse\fR tree has collections of annotations.

.PP
Returns a \fIerl_parse\fR tree where each location \fIL\fR is replaced by the value returned by \fIerl_anno:new(L)\fR. The term \fITerm\fR is traversed in a depth-first, left-to-right fashion.


.RE
.B
\fBnormalise(AbsTerm) -> Data\fR
\fB                   when AbsTerm :: abstract_expr(), Data :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts the abstract form \fIAbsTerm\fR of a term into a conventional Erlang data structure (that is, the term itself). This function is the inverse of \fIabstract/1\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBparse_exprs(Tokens) -> {ok, ExprList} | {error, ErrorInfo}\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         Tokens :: [token()],\fR
\fB                         ExprList :: [abstract_expr()],\fR
\fB                         ErrorInfo :: error_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Parses \fITokens\fR as if it was a list of expressions.

.PP
Returns one of the following:

{ok, ExprList}
.RS 2
The parsing was successful. 
\fIExprList\fR is a list of the abstract forms of the parsed expressions.

.RE

{error, ErrorInfo}
.RS 2
An error occurred.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBparse_form(Tokens) -> {ok, AbsForm} | {error, ErrorInfo}\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        Tokens :: [token()],\fR
\fB                        AbsForm :: abstract_form(),\fR
\fB                        ErrorInfo :: error_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Parses \fITokens\fR as if it was a form.

.PP
Returns one of the following:

{ok, AbsForm}
.RS 2
The parsing was successful. 
\fIAbsForm\fR is the abstract form of the parsed form.

.RE

{error, ErrorInfo}
.RS 2
An error occurred.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBparse_term(Tokens) -> {ok, Term} | {error, ErrorInfo}\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        Tokens :: [token()],\fR
\fB                        Term :: term(),\fR
\fB                        ErrorInfo :: error_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Parses \fITokens\fR as if it was a term.

.PP
Returns one of the following:

{ok, Term}
.RS 2
The parsing was successful. 
\fITerm\fR is the Erlang term corresponding to the token list.

.RE

{error, ErrorInfo}
.RS 2
An error occurred.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBtokens(AbsTerm, MoreTokens) -> Tokens\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    AbsTerm :: abstract_expr(),\fR
\fB                    MoreTokens :: [token()],\fR
\fB                    Tokens :: [token()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Generates a list of tokens representing the abstract form \fIAbsTerm\fR of an expression. Optionally, \fIMoreTokens\fR is appended.


.RE
